            <p>259 W 45&#45; St<lb/>
                Sunday evening<lb/>
                N.York Oct 5&#47;84<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                My dear friend<lb/></p>
            <p>You no doubt recollect<lb/> Mr Spurzheim Levison late of St Louis<lb/> &#38; once a resident of Phila&#58; he is now<lb/> lying at the St Lukes Hospital in this<lb/> city afflicted with an incurable disease<lb/> &#38; his death is only a matter of com&#45;<lb/>paratively a few days the doctors think<lb/> he may live a week or ten days&#8212;he<lb/> expressed a wish to me last Friday<lb/> that he would like very much to<lb/> see you&#44; I asked him whether I<lb/> should write you to come out he<lb/> said no&#44; but &#34;if you should happen<lb/> to be in the city to ask you to call<lb/> on him&#34;¬ù&#45;&#45;he is perfectly aware of<lb/> his situation &#38; quite resigned to<lb/> his fate &#38; always been true to his<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Faith&#8212;so I thought it my duty to<lb/> let you know&#8212;Could you find it<lb/> convenient to come over to see<lb/> him I think it would be a great<lb/> satisfaction to him altho I know<lb/> that your duties during the Holy<lb/> Days are not of the lightest&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Should you conclude to come over<lb/> &#38; I could be of any service to you a<lb/> telegram will reach me at my<lb/> house before 9 oC am or you can<lb/> make it convenient to dine with<lb/> me or dear Mother who would<lb/> no doubt desire her remembrance<lb/> did she know I was  writing you<lb/> with my Kindest regards &#38; wishing<lb/> you the compliments of the season<lb/> in which Mrs Allen joins I am<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly<lb/>												
                H.S. Allen<lb/></p>
            <p>St. Lukes Hospital is<lb/>
                5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Avenue &#38; 54<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/></p>
        </body>
